1
00:00:05,266 --> 00:00:06,198
Up to now,

2
00:00:06,198 --> 00:00:07,955
we have seen how are formed

3
00:00:07,955 --> 00:00:10,719
celestial bodies that compose the universe, how they evolve

4
00:00:10,719 --> 00:00:12,525
and what are the physical phenomenons

5
00:00:12,525 --> 00:00:15,218
which give them their
mass and luminosity.

6
00:00:15,218 --> 00:00:17,684
But what for the 
Universe as a whole ?

7
00:00:17,684 --> 00:00:21,000
What is its origin?
How does it evolve with time?

8
00:00:21,000 --> 00:00:24,306
What will become of it ?
What is his global composition ?

9
00:00:24,306 --> 00:00:28,796
All these question are closely linked,
and belong to the field of cosmology.

10
00:00:29,344 --> 00:00:32,108
The theory 
which currently best explains

11
00:00:32,108 --> 00:00:34,372
all observations that 
are at our disposal 

12
00:00:34,372 --> 00:00:38,162
is the Big Bang theory, where 
the Universe was born of one initial explosion,

13
00:00:38,163 --> 00:00:40,779
some 13, 8 billion years ago,

14
00:00:40,779 --> 00:00:44,787
followed by an extremely rapid 
expansion, called inflation,

15
00:00:44,787 --> 00:00:49,577
then, a slower expansion,
as was found in twenties-thirties.

16
00:00:50,289 --> 00:00:52,133
Since the years 2000,

17
00:00:52,133 --> 00:00:54,870
we know that this 
expansion is accelerated,

18
00:00:54,870 --> 00:00:59,051
but the reason for this remains
completely unknown.

19
00:00:59,051 --> 00:01:02,791
This can be explained only by invoking
the existence of a repulsive force,

20
00:01:02,791 --> 00:01:06,541
due to some unknown form of 
energy called dark energy,

21
00:01:06,542 --> 00:01:09,312
and that would counteract 
the gravitational force,

22
00:01:09,314 --> 00:01:12,504
which tends to make the
Universe contract itself.

23
00:01:13,722 --> 00:01:15,923
So we said that the 
Universe is expanding,

24
00:01:15,923 --> 00:01:18,352
that doesn't mean that the 
Universe was born in one point

25
00:01:18,352 --> 00:01:20,498
and is expanding like 
a spherical ball.

26
00:01:20,498 --> 00:01:23,687
But it means that all points are
growing further apart from each other 

27
00:01:23,687 --> 00:01:26,877
with some factor,
called the expansion factor.

28
00:01:26,893 --> 00:01:28,823
So for example, here,

29
00:01:28,823 --> 00:01:32,891
we have a certain distance which 
becomes longer as the Universe is growing.

30
00:01:32,891 --> 00:01:34,821
We have another distance here,

31
00:01:35,143 --> 00:01:39,523
which also becomes longer
by a certain factor, etc, etc.

32
00:01:39,886 --> 00:01:42,306
and the same for the distance here.

33
00:01:44,516 --> 00:01:49,586
and if we call r' the distance here
and r the distance here between two points,

34
00:01:49,986 --> 00:01:53,806
we have r' = a * r,

35
00:01:54,242 --> 00:01:57,562
where a is what we call
the expansion factor.

36
00:02:01,103 --> 00:02:03,633
So lets look at this expansion 
in more details.

37
00:02:03,972 --> 00:02:07,382
So here we have a grid
representing the metric

38
00:02:07,382 --> 00:02:10,491
defining how we measure coordinates 
in the Universe .

39
00:02:10,491 --> 00:02:13,201
and this grid will 
evolve with time,

40
00:02:13,201 --> 00:02:16,571
so time flows like this.

41
00:02:17,205 --> 00:02:20,686
and we can localize objects on this 
grid in various ways.

42
00:02:20,686 --> 00:02:24,296
For example,
we put an origin here

43
00:02:25,278 --> 00:02:28,128
so the origin will be here,

44
00:02:28,635 --> 00:02:31,275
at an instant t later

45
00:02:31,585 --> 00:02:34,695
We take an object 
at a coordinate X.

46
00:02:35,683 --> 00:02:38,301
And when we let the system 
evolve with time,

47
00:02:38,301 --> 00:02:40,513
the X coordinate hasn't changed,

48
00:02:40,513 --> 00:02:45,327
for example, we take a section here
and a section there to go to X.

49
00:02:45,327 --> 00:02:48,719
And we take a section here, 
a section there, to go to X.

50
00:02:48,719 --> 00:02:51,589
So X is what we call 
the comobile coordinate,

51
00:02:51,589 --> 00:02:53,875
which moves with the reference grid.

52
00:02:57,644 --> 00:03:00,899
We can also localise 
objects in a different way. 

53
00:03:00,899 --> 00:03:06,239
We can say that the distance from
O and X is the distance r, which is here.

54
00:03:07,137 --> 00:03:09,567
so r(t).

55
00:03:10,784 --> 00:03:14,580
and then, a moment later,
the distance r(t) has grown.

56
00:03:14,580 --> 00:03:18,700
so this r(t) will be equal

57
00:03:18,705 --> 00:03:23,255
to a certain expansion factor
times the co-mobile coordinate.

58
00:03:23,471 --> 00:03:27,531
So a(t) is the expansion 
factor of the Universe.

59
00:03:27,723 --> 00:03:30,792
Now we will see
how all this evolves.

60
00:03:30,792 --> 00:03:36,322
So, as we said, r(t)
is equal to a(t) times X.

61
00:03:37,407 --> 00:03:39,517
Of course we can also write

62
00:03:40,350 --> 00:03:44,270
that X = r(t) / a(t).

63
00:03:44,926 --> 00:03:47,456
Then, if we derive the expression
to get the velocity,

64
00:03:47,463 --> 00:03:50,751
we will try here to 
recover Hubble's law.

65
00:03:50,751 --> 00:03:55,424
We will have here da/dt times X
because X doesn't change with time.

66
00:03:55,424 --> 00:03:58,093
So if we input X here, 
we will have,

67
00:03:58,093 --> 00:04:02,503
that r', that is V(r, t),

68
00:04:03,141 --> 00:04:09,259
will be equal to
a'(t)/a(t),

69
00:04:09,259 --> 00:04:10,749
I just introduced X here,

70
00:04:11,412 --> 00:04:13,162
times r(t).

71
00:04:13,822 --> 00:04:16,802
And what we will do here,
we will write that this,

72
00:04:17,278 --> 00:04:21,518
is H(t), and this is the expansion 
rate of the Universe.

73
00:04:24,512 --> 00:04:26,298
So we had an 
expansion factor,

74
00:04:26,298 --> 00:04:28,660
a(t), while this is a ratio a'/a,

75
00:04:28,660 --> 00:04:30,720
that is an expansion 
rate. So now,

76
00:04:30,720 --> 00:04:31,671
we can also write

77
00:04:31,671 --> 00:04:34,411
that V(r0, t0),

78
00:04:35,464 --> 00:04:41,694
is equal to H(t0) times r(t0).

79
00:04:42,136 --> 00:04:43,189
In other words,

80
00:04:43,189 --> 00:04:47,509
we have here Hubble's law.

81
00:04:47,792 --> 00:04:53,502
Namely, V = H0 times r,

82
00:04:54,210 --> 00:04:57,430
that is to say, times the distance
that separates us from an object.

83
00:04:57,435 --> 00:05:01,052
So what we wrote here, is nothing 
other than Hubble's law.

84
00:05:06,348 --> 00:05:08,154
Then, this Hubble expansion law,

85
00:05:08,154 --> 00:05:09,284
we will write it again here:

86
00:05:09,284 --> 00:05:11,943
V = H0 times D.

87
00:05:12,531 --> 00:05:15,251
That was Hubble in 1929.

88
00:05:15,255 --> 00:05:18,773
But actually, the idea was also
proposed by Georges Lemaître,

89
00:05:18,773 --> 00:05:22,553
a belgian astrophysicist, in 1927.

90
00:05:23,748 --> 00:05:26,628
Drawing this law, as
we have already seen,

91
00:05:26,956 --> 00:05:31,480
it connects the distance,
long distances indeed,

92
00:05:31,480 --> 00:05:33,500
measured in mega parsecs (Mpc),

93
00:05:33,506 --> 00:05:35,701
to the velocity, 
also large velocities,

94
00:05:35,701 --> 00:05:38,548
measured in km per second (km/s).

95
00:05:38,548 --> 00:05:41,553
That is what we call
the recession velocity of galaxies.

96
00:05:41,553 --> 00:05:43,813
And we have a linear law

97
00:05:45,018 --> 00:05:49,018
between velocity and distance.

98
00:05:49,197 --> 00:05:52,807
and what H0 measures, is the 
slope of this line.

99
00:05:55,315 --> 00:05:59,519
The present value of H0
isn't very well known.

100
00:05:59,519 --> 00:06:02,631
To date there is a 10% error
margin on the exact value,

101
00:06:02,631 --> 00:06:05,523
perhaps a bit better in
the more optimistic cases. 

102
00:06:05,523 --> 00:06:10,683
it amounts to 70 km/s per Mpc.

103
00:06:11,250 --> 00:06:15,020
Right, these units may seem
strange but they are indeed km/s

104
00:06:15,291 --> 00:06:16,796
per Mpc that are measured.

105
00:06:16,796 --> 00:06:18,844
Now, the units can
be simplified.

106
00:06:18,844 --> 00:06:22,754
The true dimension of H0,
is in fact the inverse of a time.

107
00:06:25,845 --> 00:06:29,038
Thus, 1/H0 belongs of course to 
the time dimension.

108
00:06:29,038 --> 00:06:31,473
and is actually the age of the Universe.

109
00:06:31,473 --> 00:06:32,244
So why?

110
00:06:32,244 --> 00:06:35,154
Becase if we know the distance
and the velocity of a point,

111
00:06:35,694 --> 00:06:38,545
we can find the time needed

112
00:06:38,545 --> 00:06:41,478
for that point to be 
in contact with us.

113
00:06:41,478 --> 00:06:44,048
So, we have an expanding universe,

114
00:06:44,053 --> 00:06:47,138
all points were in contact 
at the beginning,

115
00:06:47,138 --> 00:06:49,128
at the Big Bang.

116
00:06:49,128 --> 00:06:53,888
and 1 / H0 later,
13,8 billion years later,

117
00:06:54,492 --> 00:06:56,852
the Universe has its present
shape, its present size.

118
00:06:57,368 --> 00:07:00,563
So we have an expanding universe;
now, what is the link with

119
00:07:00,563 --> 00:07:03,867
what is called the redshift,
the cosmological red shift?

120
00:07:03,867 --> 00:07:07,277
We can write the Doppler effect,

121
00:07:07,769 --> 00:07:08,989
namely the ratio dλ / λ.

122
00:07:09,360 --> 00:07:12,280
This is λ observed minus λ 
emitted divided by λ emitted,

123
00:07:13,486 --> 00:07:17,575
which is equal to dv/c,

124
00:07:17,575 --> 00:07:18,815
that is

125
00:07:20,005 --> 00:07:21,045
the Doppler effect,

126
00:07:21,668 --> 00:07:24,248
that we had seen in Chapter 3.2.

127
00:07:24,923 --> 00:07:27,088
Now we have seen that
following Hubble's law,

128
00:07:27,088 --> 00:07:31,334
that V equals H times distance,

129
00:07:31,334 --> 00:07:32,926
so here, we have a differential 

130
00:07:32,926 --> 00:07:35,109
hence we also have a differential there.

131
00:07:35,109 --> 00:07:37,519
We have the constant c which stays here.

132
00:07:37,934 --> 00:07:42,114
H, as we said, is a'/a,

133
00:07:43,677 --> 00:07:46,157
and we have dr / c which stays here.

134
00:07:46,541 --> 00:07:50,630
Now a certain time dt is needed
to travel the distance dr with the velocity c.

135
00:07:50,630 --> 00:07:53,180
So we could write that as: 

136
00:07:53,180 --> 00:07:57,330
(a'/a)*dt.

137
00:07:58,422 --> 00:07:59,770
Now, what does this mean?

138
00:07:59,770 --> 00:08:02,550
Re-arranging these two terms here,

139
00:08:02,846 --> 00:08:05,836
it means that dλ / λ is equal...

140
00:08:06,506 --> 00:08:08,502
remembering that a' is da/dt,

141
00:08:08,502 --> 00:08:11,712
and then we have dt/a left. 

142
00:08:11,725 --> 00:08:16,489
So in the end, we obtain dλ /λ = da/a.

143
00:08:16,489 --> 00:08:18,529
This is a differential equation

144
00:08:18,532 --> 00:08:19,506
of the first order.

145
00:08:19,506 --> 00:08:20,661
The solution to this,

146
00:08:20,661 --> 00:08:23,801
is λ(a) equals a certain constant K

147
00:08:24,358 --> 00:08:25,268
times a.

148
00:08:26,072 --> 00:08:27,922
Thus, at the present epoch,

149
00:08:29,729 --> 00:08:31,499
we have a = 1,

150
00:08:32,484 --> 00:08:36,500
so we have that λ_emitted (1)

151
00:08:36,500 --> 00:08:39,856
is equal to λ_observed.

152
00:08:39,856 --> 00:08:42,382
Because at present, 
the wavelength,

153
00:08:42,382 --> 00:08:44,907
with an expansion factor of 1,

154
00:08:44,907 --> 00:08:47,812
the emission and observation 
wavelengths are the same.

155
00:08:47,812 --> 00:08:49,248
So we have a = 1 here,

156
00:08:49,248 --> 00:08:54,838
and this implies that the constant
K is equal to  λ_observed.

157
00:08:54,839 --> 00:08:57,509
This is simply the Doppler effect.

158
00:08:57,510 --> 00:09:01,610
For a universe with an expansion factor of 1.

159
00:09:01,977 --> 00:09:04,967
Now, if we re-arrange
the results here,

160
00:09:06,512 --> 00:09:11,782
what we will get is that
λ obs / λ emit

161
00:09:12,792 --> 00:09:14,842
is equal to 1/a.

162
00:09:14,842 --> 00:09:16,742
It is exactly this equation

163
00:09:16,742 --> 00:09:20,332
once we have replaced the 
K constant by λ_obs.

164
00:09:20,332 --> 00:09:23,230
We also have the
Doppler effect formula,

165
00:09:23,230 --> 00:09:27,510
telling us that
(λ_obs minus λ_emit) / λ_emit

166
00:09:27,961 --> 00:09:29,842
is equal to V/c,
as we have seen,

167
00:09:29,842 --> 00:09:32,279
and we will set this as being equal to z.

168
00:09:32,279 --> 00:09:33,549
and this will be,

169
00:09:33,767 --> 00:09:37,967
by definition, the famous red shift.

170
00:09:39,235 --> 00:09:42,029
Now, if we gather
these two equations,

171
00:09:42,029 --> 00:09:43,256
we see that we will have :

172
00:09:43,256 --> 00:09:46,556
λ_obs / λ_emit

173
00:09:47,427 --> 00:09:49,217
= 1/a,

174
00:09:49,509 --> 00:09:51,809
namely the inverse of the expansion factor.

175
00:09:51,969 --> 00:09:54,350
But it is also equal to 1 + z.

176
00:09:54,350 --> 00:09:56,310
This implies that, if we 
want to know

177
00:09:56,480 --> 00:09:59,407
the red shift of
an object,

178
00:09:59,407 --> 00:10:03,150
we measure a given 
observed wavelength.

179
00:10:03,150 --> 00:10:05,770
let's take for example
a line in a spectrum:

180
00:10:05,778 --> 00:10:09,439
if we know 
its wavelength at rest,

181
00:10:09,439 --> 00:10:13,119
in other words the emission wavelength,
the intrinsic wavelength of the line,

182
00:10:13,119 --> 00:10:15,601
then we can find
the redshift z.

183
00:10:16,582 --> 00:10:18,862
That is the well known equation

184
00:10:19,561 --> 00:10:22,811
of the cosmological Doppler effect.

185
00:10:25,788 --> 00:10:27,152
Now an example.

186
00:10:27,152 --> 00:10:31,154
Lets take the Hubble Deep Field, as
we did several times before in this class.

187
00:10:31,154 --> 00:10:34,505
We see that there are many 
galaxies of all colours.

188
00:10:34,505 --> 00:10:38,501
Some are blue,
others are rather green,

189
00:10:38,501 --> 00:10:41,587
yet others are red, like here,
and there are two reason for that.

190
00:10:41,587 --> 00:10:44,267
First of all, galaxies
have intrinsic colours.

191
00:10:44,271 --> 00:10:47,326
Some have blue and 
hot stars, just born.

192
00:10:47,326 --> 00:10:49,541
Such galaxies have an intrinsic
blue colour.

193
00:10:49,541 --> 00:10:52,974
Others will have for example
a lot of dust making their colour redder,

194
00:10:52,974 --> 00:10:55,115
or contain a population of old stars,

195
00:10:55,115 --> 00:10:56,088
with low masses.

196
00:10:56,088 --> 00:10:57,478
So there are multiple reasons

197
00:10:57,478 --> 00:10:59,807
for the observed colours of galaxies. 

198
00:10:59,807 --> 00:11:02,961
But one additional reason is the
cosmological red shift.

199
00:11:02,961 --> 00:11:06,051
For that we can draw

200
00:11:06,052 --> 00:11:08,772
the spectrum of a galaxy

201
00:11:08,901 --> 00:11:10,541
in a schematic way.

202
00:11:10,970 --> 00:11:13,463
So a galaxy spectrum
resembles this.

203
00:11:13,463 --> 00:11:15,211
There are stars in a galaxy,

204
00:11:15,211 --> 00:11:18,121
so we will have the Break

205
00:11:18,121 --> 00:11:20,556
at 4 000 angströms,
Balmer's Break,

206
00:11:20,556 --> 00:11:23,256
that we had already seen in the 
chapter dedicated to hydrogen.

207
00:11:23,256 --> 00:11:25,300
So here, we have a typical feature

208
00:11:25,675 --> 00:11:27,725
at 4 000 angströms,

209
00:11:27,971 --> 00:11:29,264
if the galaxy is at rest,

210
00:11:29,264 --> 00:11:31,977
without any cosmological red shift.

211
00:11:31,977 --> 00:11:34,572
Now this is the wavelength,

212
00:11:34,572 --> 00:11:37,752
of λ_emission when at rest.

213
00:11:37,755 --> 00:11:42,275
And λ_observed will be equal to (1 + z)

214
00:11:43,324 --> 00:11:44,842
times λ_emitted.

215
00:11:44,842 --> 00:11:48,361
So, if we have an object
with a very high red shift,

216
00:11:48,361 --> 00:11:49,701
5 for instance,

217
00:11:49,701 --> 00:11:52,968
we will multiply 4000 by 5+1 or 6.

218
00:11:53,242 --> 00:11:54,272
So we will have

219
00:11:54,272 --> 00:11:57,498
wavelengths that will move 
like this, far into the red.

220
00:11:57,499 --> 00:12:00,643
I will put here again the wavelength, and
there the flux, since we have a spectrum,

221
00:12:00,643 --> 00:12:02,803
so we will multiply the whole spectrum

222
00:12:03,279 --> 00:12:05,269
by that factor (1 + z).

223
00:12:06,051 --> 00:12:08,770
So we will find here again the break,

224
00:12:08,770 --> 00:12:12,725
that was seen before at rest, 
but now (1 + z) times farther. 

225
00:12:12,725 --> 00:12:15,665
and the spectrum will be
stretched by a factor (1 + z).

226
00:12:15,805 --> 00:12:19,565
So everything is stretched
by a factor (1 + z) in cosmology. 

227
00:12:19,760 --> 00:12:22,351
So now, if I add filters

